 * /rankings/how-tennis-rankings-work/ — General "how rankings work" hub-style explainer.
 * Codex Round 3 evergreen cluster #2 (Rankings Explained).
 *
 * Search intent: someone who just wants to understand the system overall.
 * Does NOT cover per-tournament point tables — that's the ATP/WTA sister pages.
 * Does NOT cover live-vs-official intricacies — that's the dedicated explainer.
 */
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import FaqBlock from '../../components/FaqBlock.astro';

const title = 'How Tennis Rankings Work — ATP and WTA Explained (2026) | SUPER.TENNIS';
const h1 = 'How Tennis Rankings Work';
const metaDescription = 'How tennis rankings work in 2026: the rolling 52-week point system used by both ATP and WTA, why rankings change every Monday, how many results count (ATP: best 19, WTA: best 16), mandatory tournaments, and the difference between rankings and Race standings.';
const publishedDate = '2026-05-17';

const quickAnswer = "Both ATP and WTA rankings are 52-week rolling point totals. Players earn points by reaching specific rounds at sanctioned tournaments; the bigger the event, the more points are awarded. Each Monday after a tournament ends, the player keeps the points they just earned and loses the points they earned at the same tournament 52 weeks ago. Only the player's best results count — ATP uses the best 19 results, WTA uses the best 16. Skipping a mandatory event means the player still loses last year's points without earning replacement points, so rankings can drop without playing.";

const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'How often are tennis rankings updated?',
    a: 'Every Monday. The ATP and WTA both publish updated rankings each Monday morning, reflecting the results of tournaments that finished the previous week. During the year-end ATP Finals and WTA Finals, the final official rankings of the season are published the Monday after those events.',
  },
  {
    q: "What's the difference between ATP and WTA ranking calculations?",
    a: "Both tours use a 52-week rolling system, but two key differences exist. (1) Results counted: ATP counts a player's best 19 results, WTA counts the best 16. (2) Mandatory-event structure: each tour designates certain tournaments as mandatory, and skipping them counts as a zero-point result, which can drag the ranking down. Both tours award 2,000 points for winning a Grand Slam.",
  },
  {
    q: 'What is a "Race" in tennis rankings?',
    a: 'The Race (ATP Race to Turin / WTA Race to the WTA Finals) is a year-to-date points-only standings that tracks who qualifies for the year-end championships. Unlike the regular rankings (rolling 52 weeks), the Race only counts points earned in the current calendar year. The top 8 in the Race at season\'s end qualify for the ATP Finals / WTA Finals.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Can a player drop in rankings without playing?',
    a: "Yes. If a player skips an event where they earned points 52 weeks earlier, those old points expire ('drop off') without being replaced, lowering their total. This is why injured players and those on extended breaks see steady ranking drops even while resting. Both tours offer 'protected ranking' status to players returning from long absences (typically 6+ months for injury, or maternity for WTA).",
  },
  {
    q: 'Are there separate rankings for doubles?',
    a: 'Yes. Both ATP and WTA maintain a separate doubles ranking, calculated independently from singles. Many top doubles specialists never play singles at all. The doubles ranking uses similar 52-week rolling logic but with different point distributions and mandatory-event lists.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How do rankings affect tournament seeding?',
    a: 'Tournament seeding is based on the official ranking the day the draw is made. The top 32 players in singles (or top 16 in smaller draws) are placed at fixed positions to ensure top seeds don\'t meet until later rounds. A player ranked No. 1 cannot face the No. 2 before the final, the No. 3 or 4 cannot meet the top two before the semifinals, and so on through quarterfinals (5-8), round of 16 (9-16), and round of 32 (17-32).',
  },
  {
    q: 'What is "defending points"?',
    a: "A player is 'defending points' at a tournament when they earned points at the same tournament 52 weeks ago that are about to expire. To keep their ranking stable, they need to match (or beat) their previous result. If Player X won 1,000 points by reaching the final of a tournament last year, they're defending 1,000 points this year — losing in the first round means they lose 990 points (1,000 expiring, only 10 earned).",
  },
];

const articleJsonLd = {
